   Notre intervention au Bangladesh

   Despite economic indicators constantly progressing, about 31,5 per cent
   of the population is living under the threshold of poverty.

   Following massive population movements from the Rakhine State in
   Myanmar in August 2017, large numbers of Rohgingya and members of
   others ethnic minorities crossed the border with Bangladesh. Currently
   about one million people have taken shelter in the camps and villages
   in Cox’s Bazar. More than 40 per cent of the children are stunted, and
   the severe acute malnutrition rates are far above the emergency
   thresholds of WHO.

   The country is also one of the most vulnerable to climatic disasters.
   In May 2017, heavy rains and landslides caused by typhoon Mora affected
   more than nine million people.

   In 2017, we responded to three major emergencies: the Rohingya crisis,
   typhoon Mora, and heavy floods in the northwest regions. In partnership
   with several local and international organisations, we organised the
   prevention and treatment of acute malnutrition, as well as the support
   to vulnerable people in formal and informal camps, by direct
   interventions in nutrition and health, mental health and care
   practices, and water, sanitation and hygiene. In the region, we are
   also working outside of the camps.

   In parallel, our teams continued the activities of disaster risk
   reduction, strengthening the resilience of communities and authorities
   to face disasters, and supporting the authorities in the fight against
   acute undernutrition.

   Country Coordination Office Project

   01/07/2017 to 30/06/2020 Nationwide
   28,62,66,530 BDT

   The aim of this project is to support the project to achieve its
   objectives by providing technical and management support from Country
   Coordination level.

   NGOAB approval Ref: 03.09.2666.657.68.577.17- 182 Date: 12/09/2017

   START FUND BANGLADESH FOR RAPID EMERGENCY RESPONSE

   01/07/2018 to 31/06/2021 in 56 districts
   117,97,58,000 BDT

   The Start Fund’s overall aim is to ensure that people affected by
   crisis will be supported by a decentralized, diverse and collaborative
   ecosystem of civil society organizations with the means to respond
   rapidly, efficiently and appropriately. It aims to reach 600,000
   disaster-affected people

   NGOAB approval Ref: 03.09.2666.657.68.071.18-355 Date: 11/07/2018

   Multi-sectoral program to improve the health and nutritional status of
   vulnerable populations in Cox’s bazar district – Phase 2

   01/01/2019 to 31/12/2020 in Cox’s Bazar district

   486,56,38,000 BDT

   The aim is to implement a high quality integrated program to address
   acute and chronic vulnerabilities of residents of Cox’s Bazar district.
   The objectif is to support 12,97,929 people.

   NGOAB approval Ref: 03.09.2666.657.68.159.18-764 Date: 21/01/2019

   Please follow us on
   Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/actionagainsthunger.bd
   Youtube:https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCYoq8usMF3gklyBBYOil6Kg
