   Notre intervention au Liban

   The parliamentary elections in May represented a key moment for the
   country, since elections had not been held for nine years.

   This event coincided with the launch of a new electoral system, which
   partially changed the political leadership and, with it, certain
   attitudes towards the management of refugees. After eight years of
   conflict in Syria, refugee management continues to be one of the more
   pressing issues. This has a profound impact on the access to basic
   services and livelihoods, not only for the refugees themselves but also
   for the host population. The Lebanese Government estimates that the
   country hosts more than 1.5 million Syrian refugees, which is one of
   the largest concentrations of refugees per capita in the world. Nearly
   600,000 Syrian refugees have no recognised refugee status. As a result,
   these people do not have access to the different forms of assistance
   and support provided by the United Nations High Commissioner for
   Refugees (UNHCR) and other refugee assistance programmes.

   Our teams in the country are present both in the Bekaa region and in
   the south of the country including in difficult to reach areas, such as
   Arsal, Masharih al-Qaa and Cheeba, ensuring that basic assistance is
   provided to the populations. Our work here focuses on cash
   distributions through the KACHE system (Kit for Autonomous Cash
   Transfer in Humanitarian Emergencies) as well as continuing programmes
   in emergency aid, food security, water and sanitation, nutrition and
   protection.
   Sources : PNUD (2014), Banque Mondiale

   LB02
   Type of intervention
     * Food Security and Resources of Existence
     * Water, Sanitation and Hygiene
     * Advocacy
     * Nutrition and Health

   Country key figures

   Number of beneficiaries : 299 575

   Population : 4,4 millions

   Life expectancy : 80 years old

   GDP per capita : 10 139,2 USD

   Human Development Index : 72/187

   Operational Volume : 10 786 870 €

   Financing

   WFP, ECHO, UNICEF, UNHCR

   LB WASH 2017 Lyz Arango16

