Publication

Measuring African high burden countries’ progress towards the adoption of
national nutrition targets

   In 2012, the World Health Assembly (WHA) adopted a resolution which
   established six global targets to be achieved by 2025. In 2016,
   countries attending the Assembly reitarated their commitments and
   agreed to set national targets in line with national contexts in order
   to achieve greater progress towards global nutrition targets. The
   establishment of national targets can help set into motion a
   comprehensive planning process that identifies concrete actions and
   resources to effectively translate commitments into results.

   This scorecard highlights where high burden countries in Africa stand
   in the adoption of national nutrition targets. In general, the picture
   for African high-burden countries is mixed: more countries need to
   integrate national nutrition targets in their national policies or to
   improve them. Countries are progressing towards meeting the WHA global
   targets for stunting and for breastfeeding but progress towards
   reducing wasting remains dramatically insufficient in the continent
   concentrating the highest number of wasted children under five.
   Download

